.TH "HTMLFORMELEMENT.ELEMENTS" "3JS" "November 3, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
HTMLFormElement.elements \- HTMLFormElement: elements property
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]elements\f[B]\f[R] property of the
\f[CR]HTMLFormElement\f[R] interface returns an
\f[CR]HTMLFormControlsCollection\f[R] listing all the listed form
controls associated with the \f[CR]<form>\f[R] element.
.PP
You can access a particular form control in the returned collection by
using either an index or the element\(cqs \f[CR]name\f[R] or
\f[CR]id\f[R] attributes.
.PP
Prior to HTML 5, the returned object was an \f[CR]HTMLCollection\f[R],
on which \f[CR]HTMLFormControlsCollection\f[R] is based.
.PP
Independently, you can obtain just the number of associated form
controls using the \f[CR]length\f[R] property.
You can get a list of all of the forms contained within a given document
using the document\(cqs \f[CR]forms\f[R] property.
.SH VALUE
An \f[CR]HTMLFormControlsCollection\f[R] containing all non\-image
controls associated with the form.
This is a live collection; if form controls are associated with or
disassociated from the form, this collection will update to reflect the
change.
.PP
The form controls in the returned collection are in the same order in
which they appear in the document by following a preorder, depth\-first
traversal of the tree.
This is called \f[B]tree order\f[R].
.PP
Only the following form controls are returned:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]<button>\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]<fieldset>\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]<input>\f[R] (with the exception that any whose \f[CR]type\f[R] is
\f[CR]\(dqimage\(dq\f[R] are omitted for historical reasons)
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]<object>\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]<output>\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]<select>\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]<textarea>\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\c
.UR https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/custom-elements.html#form-associated-custom-element
form\-associated custom elements
.UE \c
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Quick syntax example
In this example, we see how to obtain the list of form controls as well
as how to access its members by index and by name or ID.
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]form\f[R] id=\(dqmy\-form\(dq>
  <\f[B]label\f[R]>
    Username:
    <\f[B]input\f[R] type=\(dqtext\(dq name=\(dqusername\(dq />
  </\f[B]label\f[R]>
  <\f[B]label\f[R]>
    Full name:
    <\f[B]input\f[R] type=\(dqtext\(dq name=\(dqfull\-name\(dq />
  </\f[B]label\f[R]>
  <\f[B]label\f[R]>
    Password:
    <\f[B]input\f[R] type=\(dqpassword\(dq name=\(dqpassword\(dq />
  </\f[B]label\f[R]>
</\f[B]form\f[R]>
.EE
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] inputs = document.getElementById(\(dqmy\-form\(dq).elements;
\f[B]const\f[R] inputByIndex = inputs[0];
\f[B]const\f[R] inputByName = inputs[\(dqusername\(dq];
.EE
.SS Associated form controls
This example demonstrates how the \f[CR]HTMLFormControlsCollection\f[R]
contains the form controls associated with the form, rather than the
controls physically nested in the \f[CR]<form>\f[R].
.PP
The first form is full, with four form controls: one
\f[CR]<fieldset>\f[R] and three \f[CR]<input>\f[R] elements.
The \f[CR]<legend>\f[R] and \f[CR]<label>\f[R] elements are not listed
form controls.
The second form is sparse, with only one nested form control: a single
\f[CR]<object>\f[R] element.
All the form controls in the full form are associated with the sparse
form via their \f[CR]form\f[R] attribute.
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]form\f[R] id=\(dqfullForm\(dq>
  This form looks full, but it has no associated form controls
  <\f[B]fieldset\f[R] form=\(dqsparseForm\(dq>
    <\f[B]legend\f[R]>This is a legend</\f[B]legend\f[R]>
    <\f[B]label\f[R]>A form control: <\f[B]input\f[R] form=\(dqsparseForm\(dq /></\f[B]label\f[R]>
    <\f[B]label\f[R]>Another form control: <\f[B]input\f[R] form=\(dqsparseForm\(dq /></\f[B]label\f[R]>
    <\f[B]label\f[R]>Yet another form control: <\f[B]input\f[R] form=\(dqsparseForm\(dq /></\f[B]label\f[R]>
  </\f[B]fieldset\f[R]>
</\f[B]form\f[R]>

<\f[B]form\f[R] id=\(dqsparseForm\(dq>
  <\f[B]object\f[R] data=\(dqlone\-form\-control.jpg\(dq>Lone form control</\f[B]object\f[R]>
</\f[B]form\f[R]>
.EE
.PP
We use the \f[CR]elements\f[R] property to get the
\f[CR]HTMLFormControlsCollection\f[R] for each form.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] sparse = document.getElementById(\(dqsparseForm\(dq).elements;
\f[B]const\f[R] full = document.getElementById(\(dqfullForm\(dq).elements;
.EE
.PP
The collection includes the form element\(cqs associated form controls,
meaning all the \f[CR]<button>\f[R], \f[CR]<fieldset>\f[R],
\f[CR]<input>\f[R], \f[CR]<object>\f[R], \f[CR]<output>\f[R],
\f[CR]<select>\f[R], \f[CR]<textarea>\f[R], and form\-associated custom
elements associated with the form, even if those elements are nested in
another form, or not nested in any form.
.IP
.EX
console.log(\(gasparse form: ${sparse.length}\(ga); \f[I]// sparse form: 5\f[R]
console.log(\(gafull form: ${full.length}\(ga); \f[I]// full form: 0\f[R]
.EE
.PP
The collection\(cqs form controls are in the same order in which they
appear in the document.
.IP
.EX
console.log(\(gafirst member: ${sparse[0].tagName}\(ga); \f[I]// first member: FIELDSET\f[R]
console.log(\(galast member: ${sparse[sparse.length \- 1].tagName}\(ga); \f[I]// last member: OBJECT\f[R]
.EE
.SS Accessing form controls
This example gets the form\(cqs element list, then iterates over the
list, looking for \f[CR]<input>\f[R] elements of type
\f[CR]\(dqtext\(dq\f[R] so that some form of processing can be performed
on them.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] inputs = document.getElementById(\(dqmy\-form\(dq).elements;

\f[I]// Iterate over the form controls\f[R]
\f[B]for\f[R] (\f[B]const\f[R] input \f[B]of\f[R] inputs) {
  \f[B]if\f[R] (input.nodeName === \(dqINPUT\(dq && input.type === \(dqtext\(dq) {
    \f[I]// Update text input\f[R]
    input.value = input.value.toLocaleUpperCase();
  }
}
.EE
.SS Disabling form controls
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] inputs = document.getElementById(\(dqmy\-form\(dq).elements;

\f[I]// Iterate over the form controls\f[R]
\f[B]for\f[R] (\f[B]const\f[R] input \f[B]of\f[R] inputs) {
  \f[I]// Disable all form controls\f[R]
  input.setAttribute(\(dqdisabled\(dq, \(dq\(dq);
}
.EE
